# Project Rules for AI Agents

## Code Style

- Use TypeScript strictly; avoid `any` unless necessary
- Prefer functional components and hooks in React
- Use meaningful names; keep functions small and focused

## Naming

- Prefer **kebab-case** for file names (e.g. `use-raid-tracker.ts`, `raid-tracker-table/index.tsx`)
- Keep exported symbols idiomatic (e.g. `useRaidTracker` is fine), but keep **file paths** kebab-case
- Avoid oversimplified names for locals and callback params (e.g. `v`, `d`, `c`, `e`); prefer descriptive names like `event`, `nextValue`, `character`, `dungeon`

## Commit Messages

Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/):

```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>
```

- **feat:** new feature (MINOR)
- **fix:** bug fix (PATCH)
- **docs:** documentation only
- **style:** formatting, no code change
- **refactor:** code change that neither fixes nor adds a feature
- **perf:** performance improvement
- **test:** adding or updating tests
- **chore:** build, CI, tooling
- **BREAKING CHANGE:** use `!` after type/scope or footer (MAJOR)

Example: `feat(auth): add login form`

## Versioning & Changelog

- Use [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/): MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH
- Version lives in `package.json`; shown in the app header via Vite `define` (`AppVersionLabel`)
- When releasing: bump `package.json` version, then add a `CHANGELOG.md` entry
- Changelog entries must describe **actual user-facing changes** included in the release (derived from commits/diff since the previous release), not just “bump version”

### Changelog format

- Follow [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/)
- File: `CHANGELOG.md` at project root
- Sections: `### Added`, `### Changed`, `### Deprecated`, `### Removed`, `### Fixed`, `### Security`
- Entry format: `## [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD`
- Add new entries at the top (above previous releases)
- Do **not** add filler entries like “version bump for release”; if a release contains no notable changes, do not cut a release (or explicitly document why)

### Version bump rules

- **PATCH** — bug fixes, minor tweaks
- **MINOR** — new features, non-breaking changes
- **MAJOR** — breaking changes (use `BREAKING CHANGE` in commit)

## Editing

- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- Preserve existing formatting and indentation
- Run linter after changes; fix any new issues

